{"title_page": "Marguerite Moore", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish orator, patriot, activist}}\n[[File:MARGUERITE MOORE A woman of the century (page 527 crop).jpg|thumb|Marguerite Moore, pictured in ''A Woman of the Century'']]\n'''Marguerite Moore''' (7 July 1849 \u2013 ?) was an Irish-Catholic orator, patriot, and activist. A nationalist and suffragist,{{sfn|McCarthy|2018|p=171}} she was referred to as the \"first suffragette\".<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\">{{cite web |title=Marguerite Moore - Waterford's Revolutionary Women 1916-1922 |url=http://www.waterfordmuseum.ie/exhibit/web/Display/article/382/12/Waterfords_Revolutionary_Women_19161922_Marguerite_Moore.html |publisher=Waterford County Museum |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and education==\nMarguerite Moore was born in [[Waterford, Ireland]], on 7 July 1849. She was educated in Ireland. Many other details about her life are unknown.{{sfn|McCarthy|2018|p=171}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1881, she sprang into a foremost place in the politics of her native land. [[Charles Stewart Parnell]] and the rest of the national and local leaders were in prison, and the existence of the great organization they had built up was imperiled. [[Anna Catherine Parnell]], the sister of Charles Stewart Parnell, called on the women of Ireland to help in the struggle.<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\" /> Mrs. Moore's patriotism, sympathy for the suffering and eloquence made of her an invaluable auxiliary. She threw herself into the struggle, which had for its aim the fixing of the Irish tenant farmer in his holding and the succoring of the tenants already evicted. She traveled throughout Ireland, teaching the doctrine of the [[Irish National Land League]], and bringing help to the victims of landlord tyranny. In all the large cities of England and Scotland, she addressed crowded meetings. After twelve months, she was arrested and sentenced to six months' imprisonment in [[Tullamore]] jail, [[County Offaly|Kings county]], Ireland.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=517}} Refusing bail, she served the entire sentence.<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\" />\n\nIn the summer of 1882, when Mr. Parnell and his followers were released from prison, the women returned into their hands the trust they had so faithfully guarded. Two years afterwards Mrs. Moore, accompanied by her family of four girls and two boys, came to the United States. Here she gained a reputation as a speaker on social matters, women's suffrage, labor questions and land reform. Any good cause found in her an able platform advocate. She used her pen in defense of the oppressed. She took a deep interest in American politics, as a believer in the single-tax doctrines. She took a prominent part in the [[New York City]] election campaigns of 1886\u201387, addressing two or three meetings each evening.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=517}} Before and after 1916, she worked as a fundraiser and public speaker, and was active in demonstrations. In 1920, she was involved in a three-and-a-half-week strike.<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\" />\n\nShe was a vice-president of the [[Universal Peace Union]], a member of the [[Woman's Press Club of New York City]], treasurer and secretary of the Parnell Branch of the [[Irish National League]], and prominent in the literary society of New York City. \n{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=517}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Attribution===\n* {{Source-attribution| {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Willard|first1=Frances Elizabeth|last2=Livermore|first2=Mary Ashton Rice|title=A Woman of the Century: Fourteen Hundred-seventy Biographical Sketches Accompanied by Portraits of Leading American Women in All Walks of Life|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Woman_of_the_Century/Marguerite_Moore|edition=Public domain|year=1893|publisher=Moulton}} }}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=McCarthy|first=Tara M.|title=Respectability and Reform: Irish American Women's Activism, 1880-1920|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y3N0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA171|date=2 April 2018|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-5436-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Marguerite Moore}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Marguerite}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:Irish suffragists]]\n[[Category:People from Waterford (city)]]\n[[Category:Irish activists]]\n[[Category:Irish women activists]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States (before 1923)]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia articles incorporating text from A Woman of the Century]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish orator, patriot, activist}}\n[[File:MARGUERITE MOORE A woman of the century (page 527 crop).jpg|thumb|Marguerite Moore, pictured in ''A Woman of the Century'']]\n'''Marguerite Moore''' (7 July 1849 \u2013 ?) was an Irish-Catholic orator, patriot, and activist. A nationalist and suffragist,{{sfn|McCarthy|2018|p=171}} she was referred to as the \"first suffragette\".<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\">{{cite web |title=Marguerite Moore - Waterford's Revolutionary Women 1916-1922 |url=http://www.waterfordmuseum.ie/exhibit/web/Display/article/382/12/Waterfords_Revolutionary_Women_19161922_Marguerite_Moore.html |publisher=Waterford County Museum |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and education==\nMarguerite Moore was born in [[Waterford, Ireland]], on 7 July 1849. She was educated in Ireland. Many other details about her life are unknown.{{sfn|McCarthy|2018|p=171}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1881, she sprang into a foremost place in the politics of her native land. [[Charles Stewart Parnell]] and the rest of the national and local leaders were in prison, and the existence of the great organization they had built up was imperiled. [[Anna Catherine Parnell]], the sister of Charles Stewart Parnell, called on the women of Ireland to help in the struggle.<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\" /> Mrs. Moore's patriotism, sympathy for the suffering and eloquence made of her an invaluable auxiliary. She threw herself into the struggle, which had for its aim the fixing of the Irish tenant farmer in his holding and the succoring of the tenants already evicted. She traveled throughout Ireland, teaching the doctrine of the [[Irish National Land League]], and bringing help to the victims of landlord tyranny. In all the large cities of England and Scotland, she addressed crowded meetings. After twelve months, she was arrested and sentenced to six months' imprisonment in [[Tullamore]] jail, [[County Offaly|Kings county]], Ireland.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=517}} Refusing bail, she served the entire sentence.<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\" />\n\nIn the summer of 1882, when Mr. Parnell and his followers were released from prison, the women returned into their hands the trust they had so faithfully guarded. Two years afterwards Mrs. Moore, accompanied by her family of four girls and two boys, came to the United States. Here she gained a reputation as a speaker on social matters, woman suffrage, labor question and land reform. Any good cause found in her an able platform advocate. She used her pen in defense of the oppressed. She took a deep interest in American politics, as a believer in the single-tax doctrines. She took a prominent part in the [[New York City]] election campaigns of 1886\u201387, addressing two or three meetings each evening.{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=517}} Before and after 1916, she worked as a fundraiser and public speaker, and was active in demonstrations. In 1920, she was involved in a three-and-a-half-week strike.<ref name=\"waterfordmuseum.ie\" />\n\nShe was a vice-president of the [[Universal Peace Union]], a member of the [[Woman's Press Club of New York City]], treasurer and secretary of the Parnell Branch of the [[Irish National League]], and prominent in the literary society of New York City. \n{{sfn|Willard|Livermore|1893|p=517}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Attribution===\n* {{Source-attribution| {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Willard|first1=Frances Elizabeth|last2=Livermore|first2=Mary Ashton Rice|title=A Woman of the Century: Fourteen Hundred-seventy Biographical Sketches Accompanied by Portraits of Leading American Women in All Walks of Life|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Woman_of_the_Century/Marguerite_Moore|edition=Public domain|year=1893|publisher=Moulton}} }}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=McCarthy|first=Tara M.|title=Respectability and Reform: Irish American Women's Activism, 1880-1920|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y3N0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA171|date=2 April 2018|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=978-0-8156-5436-0}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Marguerite Moore}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Marguerite}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:Irish suffragists]]\n[[Category:People from Waterford (city)]]\n[[Category:Irish activists]]\n[[Category:Irish women activists]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States (before 1923)]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia articles incorporating text from A Woman of the Century]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marguerite_Moore"}
{"title_page": "Mario Stoppani", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          =Mario Stoppani\n| image         =Mario stoppani pilotaggio.jpg\n| caption       =Mario Stoppani (left)\n| birth_date          = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->24 May 1895\n| death_date          = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->20 September 1959\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| birth_place  =[[Lovere]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n| death_place  =\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      =\n| allegiance    =Italy\n| branch        =Aviation\n| serviceyears  =\n| rank          = ''[[Sergeant|Sergente]]''\n| unit          =[[76a Squadriglia]], [[3a Squadriglia]]\n| commands      =\n| battles       =\n| awards        =2 Silver awards of [[Medal for Military Valor]], Russian [[Cross of St. George]], both a Silver and a Gold [[Medal of Aeronautic Valor]]\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =Made 15 first flights and set 41 aviation records\n}}\n''[[Sergeant|Sergente]]'' '''Mario Stoppani''' (24 May 1895 \u2013 20 September 1959) was a [[World War I]] [[flying ace]] credited with six aerial victories.<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/italy/stoppani.php Retrieved 2 April 2010.</ref> His valor earned him two Silver awards of the [[Medal for Military Valor]] and the Russian [[Cross of St. George]] during the World War I.\n\nAfter the war, after a short spell as an aviation instructor, in 1927 Stoppani began a long career as a test pilot and an extensive career setting aeronautical records. He would continue as a test pilot throughout World War II and beyond. While associated with aeronautical designer [[Filippo Zappata]], Stoppani would make 15 first flights and set 41 aeronautical records, one of which still stands. In the course of these feats, Stoppani earned both a Silver and a Gold Medal for Aeronautical Valor. Post World War II, he worked for [[Breda]] and [[SIAI Marchetti]].\n\n==Early life==\nMario Stoppani was born in [[Lovere]], [[Kingdom of Italy]] on 24 May 1895. He [[apprentice]]d as an auto mechanic at age 15, circa 1910. On 6 November 1913, he enlisted in the ''Battaglione Aviatori'' (Aviators' Battalion). In February 1915, he was selected for pilot's training at [[Pisa]].<ref name=fronts161>Franks et al 1997, p. 161.</ref>\n\n==World War I==\nIn June 1915, Stoppani was posted to an operational unit, ''3a Squadriglia''. Based at Medeuzza, he flew a Macchi Parasol on reconnaissance patrols. He was awarded a Silver [[Medal for Military Valor]] for his exploits during August through November 1915.<ref name=fronts161/>\n\nIn January 1916, he was seconded to instructor duty at [[Malpensa]]. He stayed there until May, when he was assigned to newly formed ''76a Squadriglia'', based at La Comina. Flying a [[Nieuport 11]], he scored his first aerial victory on 9 July 1916, sharing it with [[Luigi Olivari]]. By 1 December 1916, he had tallied five more, including a shared win with [[Luigi Olivi]]. He was recommended for a second Silver Medal for Military Valor in November; that same month he was asked to become a test pilot for [[Gio. Ansaldo & C.#Aircraft production|Ansaldo]].<ref name=fronts161/>\n\nIn January 1917, Stoppani was awarded the Russian [[Cross of Saint George]], Third Class. In March, he moved to Genoa to begin his duties with Ansaldo by testing the [[Ansaldo A.1 Balilla]] and SVA.<ref>Note: Type of Ansaldo SVA not specified.</ref> In June 1917, he finally received his second Silver Medal. Stoppani finished out the war as a test pilot.<ref name=fronts161/> He scored all of his victories flying in the [[Nieuport 11]], becoming one of the most successful pilots in the type.\n\n==Post World War I==\nStoppani made a career of aviation. He became an instructor with [[Societ\u00e0 Aeronautica Italiana|SAI]], first at [[Foggia]], then at [[Passignano sul Trasimeno]] in 1925.<ref name=aces82>Franks 2000, p. 82.</ref> In 1927, he moved to [[Trieste]] and resumed test piloting, for [[SISA Airline]]. He then became the chief test pilot for [[CANT (aviation)|CANT aircraft company]] until mid-World War II, circa 1943. During his career with CANT, he was closely associated with designer [[Filippo Zappata]]; the association led to Stoppani making fifteen first flights and setting 41 flying records. Stoppani was awarded both a Silver and Gold Medal for Aeronautical Valor for his efforts.<ref name=fronts161/> He still holds the distance record for a seaplane in a closed circuit; in 1937, he covered 3,231 miles without landing, piloting a [[CRDA CANT Z.506]].<ref>http://www.airspacemag.com/flight-today/Ten_Most_Wanted.html {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120731080911/http://www.airspacemag.com/flight-today/Ten_Most_Wanted.html |date=2012-07-31 }} Retrieved 2 April 2010.</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, he worked for [[Breda]] and [[SIAI Marchetti]].<ref name=aces82/> Mario Stoppani died on 20 September 1959.<ref name=fronts161/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Norman Franks|Franks, Norman]]; Guest, Russell; Alegi, Gregory.  ''Above the War Fronts: The British Two-seater Bomber Pilot and Observer Aces, the British Two-seater Fighter Observer Aces, and the Belgian, Italian, Austro-Hungarian and Russian Fighter Aces, 1914\u20131918: Volume 4 of Fighting Airmen of WWI Series: Volume 4 of Air Aces of WWI''. Grub Street, 1997. {{ISBN|1-898697-56-6}}, {{ISBN|978-1-898697-56-5}}.\n* Franks, Norman. ''Nieuport Aces of World War 1.'' Osprey Publishing, 2000. {{ISBN|1-85532-961-1}}, {{ISBN|978-1-85532-961-4}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mariostoppani.it Mario Stoppani Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stoppani, Mario}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian World War I flying aces]]\n[[Category:Test pilots]]\n[[Category:Italian aviation record holders]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of Aeronautic Valor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          =Mario Stoppani\n| image         =Mario stoppani pilotaggio.jpg\n| caption       =Mario Stoppani (left)\n| birth_date          = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->24 May 1895\n| death_date          = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->20 September 1959\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| birth_place  =[[Lovere]], [[Kingdom of Italy]]\n| death_place  =\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      =\n| allegiance    =Italy\n| branch        =Aviation\n| serviceyears  =\n| rank          = ''[[Sergeant|Sergente]]''\n| unit          =[[76a Squadriglia]], [[3a Squadriglia]]\n| commands      =\n| battles       =\n| awards        =2 Silver awards of [[Medal for Military Valor]], Russian [[Cross of St. George]], both a Silver and a Gold [[Medal of Aeronautic Valor]]\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =Made 15 first flights and set 41 aviation records\n}}\n''[[Sergeant|Sergente]]'' '''Mario Stoppani''' (24 May 1895 \u2013 20 September 1959) was a [[World War I]] [[flying ace]] credited with six aerial victories.<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/italy/stoppani.php Retrieved 2 April 2010.</ref> His valor earned him two Silver awards of the [[Medal for Military Valor]] and the Russian [[Cross of St. George]] during the World War I.\n\nAfter the war, after a short spell as an aviation instructor, in 1927 Stoppani began a long career as a test pilot and an extensive career setting aeronautical records. He would continue as a test pilot throughout World War II and beyond. While associated with aeronautical designer [[Filippo Zappata]], Stoppani would make 15 first flights and set 41 aeronautical records, one of which still stands. In the course of these feats, Stoppani earned both a Silver and a Gold Medal for Aeronautical Valor. Post World War II, he worked for [[Breda]] and [[SIAI Marchetti]].\n\n==Early life==\nMario Stoppani was born in [[Lovere]], [[Kingdom of Italy]] on 24 May 1895. He [[apprentice]]d as an auto mechanic at age 15, circa 1910. On 6 November 1913, he enlisted in the ''Battaglione Aviatori'' (Aviators' Battalion). In February 1915, he was selected for pilot's training at [[Pisa]].<ref name=fronts161>Franks et al 1997, p. 161.</ref>\n\n==World War I==\nIn June 1915, Stoppani was posted to an operational unit, ''3a Squadriglia''. Based at Medeuzza, he flew a Macchi Parasol on reconnaissance patrols. He was awarded a Silver [[Medal for Military Valor]] for his exploits during August through November 1915.<ref name=fronts161/>\n\nIn January 1916, he was seconded to instructor duty at [[Malpensa]]. He stayed there until May, when he was assigned to newly formed ''76a Squadriglia'', based at La Comina. Flying a [[Nieuport 11]], he scored his first aerial victory on 9 July 1916, sharing it with [[Luigi Olivari]]. By 1 December 1916, he had tallied five more, including a shared win with [[Luigi Olivi]]. He was recommended for a second Silver Medal for Military Valor in November; that same month he was asked to become a test pilot for [[Gio. Ansaldo & C.#Aircraft production|Ansaldo]].<ref name=fronts161/>\n\nIn January 1917, Stoppani was awarded the Russian [[Cross of Saint George]], Third Class. In March, he moved to Genoa to begin his duties with Ansaldo by testing the [[Ansaldo A.1 Balilla]] and SVA.<ref>Note: Type of Ansaldo SVA not specified.</ref> In June 1917, he finally received his second Silver Medal. Stoppani finished out the war as a test pilot.<ref name=fronts161/> He scored all of his victories flying in the [[Nieuport 11]], becoming one of the most sucessful pilots in the type.\n\n==Post World War I==\nStoppani made a career of aviation. He became an instructor with [[Societ\u00e0 Aeronautica Italiana|SAI]], first at [[Foggia]], then at [[Passignano sul Trasimeno]] in 1925.<ref name=aces82>Franks 2000, p. 82.</ref> In 1927, he moved to [[Trieste]] and resumed test piloting, for [[SISA Airline]]. He then became the chief test pilot for [[CANT (aviation)|CANT aircraft company]] until mid-World War II, circa 1943. During his career with CANT, he was closely associated with designer [[Filippo Zappata]]; the association led to Stoppani making fifteen first flights and setting 41 flying records. Stoppani was awarded both a Silver and Gold Medal for Aeronautical Valor for his efforts.<ref name=fronts161/> He still holds the distance record for a seaplane in a closed circuit; in 1937, he covered 3,231 miles without landing, piloting a [[CRDA CANT Z.506]].<ref>http://www.airspacemag.com/flight-today/Ten_Most_Wanted.html {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120731080911/http://www.airspacemag.com/flight-today/Ten_Most_Wanted.html |date=2012-07-31 }} Retrieved 2 April 2010.</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, he worked for [[Breda]] and [[SIAI Marchetti]].<ref name=aces82/> Mario Stoppani died on 20 September 1959.<ref name=fronts161/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Norman Franks|Franks, Norman]]; Guest, Russell; Alegi, Gregory.  ''Above the War Fronts: The British Two-seater Bomber Pilot and Observer Aces, the British Two-seater Fighter Observer Aces, and the Belgian, Italian, Austro-Hungarian and Russian Fighter Aces, 1914\u20131918: Volume 4 of Fighting Airmen of WWI Series: Volume 4 of Air Aces of WWI''. Grub Street, 1997. {{ISBN|1-898697-56-6}}, {{ISBN|978-1-898697-56-5}}.\n* Franks, Norman. ''Nieuport Aces of World War 1.'' Osprey Publishing, 2000. {{ISBN|1-85532-961-1}}, {{ISBN|978-1-85532-961-4}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mariostoppani.it Mario Stoppani Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stoppani, Mario}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian World War I flying aces]]\n[[Category:Test pilots]]\n[[Category:Italian aviation record holders]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of Aeronautic Valor]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorld War I:ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: sucessful \u2192 successful"