{"title_page": "Echo Fox", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox sports team\n| name         = Echo Fox\n| short_name   =\n| logo         = Echo Fox logo.png\n| logo_size    =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| city         =\n| location     =\n| parent_group =\n| founded      = {{start date|2015|12|18}}\n| folded       = November 2019\n| league       =\n| history      =\n| owner        = Khalid Jones (co-owner)\n| president    = Jared Jeffries\n| gm           = Justin Lee\n| partners     =\n| sport_label  = Divisions\n| sport        = ''[[Apex Legends]]''<br>''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]''<br>''[[Dragon Ball FighterZ]]''<br>''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]''<br>''[[Injustice 2]]''<br>''[[Madden NFL 19]]''<br>''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''<br>''[[Super Smash Bros.]]''<br>''[[Street Fighter V]]''\n| website      = {{Official URL}}\n| footnotes    =\n| fanclub      =\n}}\n\n'''Echo Fox''' was an American [[esports]] organization. It was founded on December 18, 2015 by retired basketball player [[Rick Fox]], who created Echo Fox after he purchased the [[North American League of Legends Championship Series|NA LCS]] spot of [[Gravity Gaming]].<ref name=\"BloombergFOX\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-18/former-nba-player-rick-fox-buys-esports-team-gravity|title=Former NBA Player Rick Fox Buys eSports Team Gravity|first=Scott |last=Soshnick|website=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015}}</ref> The organization had expanded into various games with teams competing in titles such as ''[[Call of Duty]]'', ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive|CS:GO]]'', ''[[Dragon Ball FighterZ]]'', ''[[Injustice 2]],'' ''[[Madden NFL 19]]'', ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'', ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'', and ''[[Street Fighter V]]''. Echo Fox had several fighting game players with championship titles and are a well known organization in the professional scene.\n\n== Controversies ==\n[[File:Rick Fox 2009.jpg|thumb|Rick Fox, co-founder of Echo Fox.]]\n\nOn December 18, 2015 [[Rick Fox]] and his business partners, Amit Razaida and Khalid Jones, entered the professional [[esports]] scene with their acquisition of the [[North American League of Legends Championship Series|NA LCS]] spot of [[Gravity Gaming]], creating a new team named Echo Fox.<ref name=\"BloombergFOX\" /> According to Razaida, he and Jones \"both offered up $1 million each to get the new team off the ground\" while Fox \"never put in any of his own money into Echo Fox.\" Fox and Raizada subsequently had a falling out, in which Raizada claims Fox attempted to extort him of $5 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://upcomer.com/lol/story/1427355/raizada-comes-forward-to-dispute-allegations-by-fox|title=Exclusive: Raizada comes forward to dispute allegations by Fox|website=upcomer.com|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Fox threatened to leave the esports team after accusing Razaida of making racist comments against him and Echo Fox CEO Jace Hall, as well as threatening Fox's family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/esports/rick-fox-leaving-echo-fox-amid-racist-abuse-from-organization-shareholder-576426|title=Rick Fox set to leave Echo Fox amid racist abuse from organization shareholder [UPDATED]|website=Dexerto.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/4/25/18516539/rick-fox-leaving-echo-fox-racism-esports|title=Rick Fox reportedly quitting his esports company, alleging racist abuse|last=Lee|first=Julia|date=2019-04-25|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> In response, Riot Games, which operates the LCS, launched an investigation. It ordered Echo Fox to remove Razaida, or it would have to sell its spot in the LCS within 60 days, saying \"hate speech, threats, and bigotry have no place in the LCS.\" With Echo Fox unable to remove Razaida, Riot Games came up with an agreement to end Echo Fox's participation in the LCS. Kroenke Sports and Entertainment agreed to a deal for the LCS slot soon after for $30.25 million, however, the deal fell through due to legal issues with their partner, Sentinels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27358667/kroenke-sports-entertainment-deal-acquire-echo-fox-falls-through|title=Kroenke Sports & Entertainment deal to acquire Echo Fox falls through|date=2019-08-10|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> After the deadline given to Echo Fox to sell their slot ended, Riot Games announced its plans to sell off the newly vacated LCS franchise spot to a new team, with most of the proceeds going to Echo Fox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/14/20805868/league-of-legends-echo-fox-sale-lcs-riot-games|title=Riot Games steps in to find buyer for Echo Fox\u2019s League of Legends franchise|last=Goslin|first=Austen|date=2019-08-14|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nRiot games selected Evil Geniuses as the organization that would acquire Echo Fox's League Championship Series slot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27708703/evil-geniuses-confirm-acquisition-echo-fox-lcs-spot|title=Evil Geniuses confirm acquisition of Echo Fox's LCS spot|date=2019-09-26|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, A lawsuit ousting general partner [[Rick Fox]] was sent to Fox by several of his business partners, stating Fox had repeatedly worked against the best interests of the company. The letter sent had several signatures including: Vision Esports head Stratton Sclavos, investor Daniel Deshe, Raizada Group manager Ravi Srivastava and Khalid Jones, who was Fox's partner in the general partnership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27714092/rick-fox-ousted-echo-fox|title=Sources: Rick Fox to be ousted from Echo Fox|date=2019-09-27|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \u00a0Fox filed a lawsuit against his business partners Amit Raizada and Stratton Sclavos alleging the two partners committed fraud, conspiracy and breach of contract against him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27759801/rick-fox-sues-business-partners-alleging-fraud-conspiracy-breach-contract|title=Rick Fox sues business partners alleging fraud, conspiracy and breach of contract|date=2019-10-03|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, with numerous rumors spreading about Echo Fox splitting apart over the lawsuits, an Echo Fox investor officially confirmed the organization was disbanded.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dotesports.com/business/news/echo-fox-reportedly-dissolves-parts-ways-with-players-and-staff |title=Echo Fox reportedly dissolves, parts ways with players and staff |date=2019-11-09 |website=Dot Esports |language=en-US |access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://win.gg/news/2920/echo-fox-investors-confirm-echo-fox-is-100-percent-dissolved |title=Echo Fox investors confirm Echo Fox is 100 percent dissolved - LOL - News - WIN.gg |last=Richman |first=Olivia |website=WIN Esports |access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=April 2020}}\n\n== ''League of Legends'' ==\nOn January 23, 2016, due to some concerns over player work-eligibility, Echo Fox was unable to submit a roster and was required to forfeit their match against [[NRG Esports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/competitive-ruling-echo-fox|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com|access-date=January 23, 2016}}</ref> Echo Fox finished last in the [[2016 Summer NA LCS]], forcing a relegation match. They defeated [[NRG Esports]] 3-0 in relegations and qualified for the 2017 NA LCS Spring Split.\n\nIn 2018, the North American [[League of Legends Championship Series#Franchising|League of Legends Championship Series]] moved to a franchised league and Echo Fox invested in a spot as a permanent partner. Echo Fox later received an equity investment from the [[New York Yankees]] and a new roster, which finished 2nd in the 2018 NA LCS Spring Split with 12 wins and 7 losses after losing a tiebreaker to [[100 Thieves]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NA LCS 2018 Spring Split {{!}} Teams and Standings|url=https://www.lolesports.com/en_US/na-lcs/na_2018_spring/standings/regular_season|website=www.lolesports.com|publisher=LoL Esports|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 16, 2019, the rosters of both Echo Fox and Echo Fox Academy were released, and the organization departed the professional ''League of Legends'' scene.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Jacob |title=Ousted from LCS, Echo Fox release players |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27402851/ousted-lcs-echo-fox-release-players |accessdate=September 26, 2019 |work=Field Level Media via ESPN |date=August 17, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== ''Counter-Strike: Global Offensive'' ==\nWhile no official reason has been given for Echo Fox allowing its players to leave, it is rumored that this was due to poor performances at both [[ELEAGUE Season 2]] and IBUYPOWER Masters 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hltv.org/news/19251/echo-fox-allows-players-to-exit|title=Echo Fox allows players to exit|work=HLTV.org|access-date=October 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref> At ELEAGUE, Echo Fox lost versus [[Virtus.pro]] (where they won only a single round on Nuke),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://esportlivescore.com/e_214950-virtuspro-vs-echo-fox-eleague.html|title=Virtus.pro vs Echo Fox - CSGO - match result - 05-11-2016|website=eSportLiveScore.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref> and versus [[G2 Esports]] (where Echo Fox lost 16\u20133 and 16\u20132 on Nuke and Dust 2 respectively).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gosugamers.net/counterstrike/tournaments/12417-eleague-season-2/matches/144301-echo-fox-vs-g2-esports|title=Echo Fox. vs G2 Esports - CS:GO - ELEAGUE Season 2 {{!}} GosuGamers|website=www.gosugamers.net|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref> At iBUYPOWER Masters 2016 Echo Fox finished a disappointing 5th\u20136th place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.12up.com/posts/4109078-echo-fox-struggles-at-ibp-masters-2016|title=Echo Fox Struggles at iBP Masters 2016|date=2016-11-14|website=12up.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\n== Fighting games ==\nEcho Fox entered the [[fighting game community]] on April 29, 2016 by signing ''[[Street Fighter V]]'' player Julio Fuentes.<ref name=\"FOXJulio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-fighting-games-sign-sfv-julio-fuentes/|title=Echo Fox gets into fighting games, sign SFV player Julio Fuentes|last1=Mueller|first1=Saira|last2=Jurek|first2=Steven|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|accessdate=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503075222/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-fighting-games-sign-sfv-julio-fuentes/|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> A month later, they would sign ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' pro [[Mew2King|Jason \"Mew2King\" Zimmerman]].<ref name=\"FOXM2K\">{{cite web|url=https://pvplive.net/c/echo-fox-signs-mew2king|title=Echo Fox Signs Mew2King|last1=Steiner|first1=Dustin|website=[[PVP Live]]|accessdate=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202050823/https://pvplive.net/c/echo-fox-signs-mew2king|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Echo Fox would make one of the biggest signings in [[esports]] history by signing seven FGC players all at once, three of which previously represented [[Evil Geniuses]]. The players were ''Street Fighter'' players [[Justin Wong]], Yusuke Momochi, Hajime \"Tokido\" Taniguchi, and Yuko \"ChocoBlanka\" Momochi, ''Mortal Kombat'' players [[SonicFox|Dominique \"SonicFox\" McLean]] and Brad \"Scar\" Vaughn, and ''Super Smash Bros.'' player [[MKLeo|Leonardo \"MKLeo\" Lopez Perez]]. At the same time, Echo Fox signed former Evil Geniuses manager Antonio \"CoolGrayAJ\" Javier as the team's new manager.<ref name=\"FOXFGC\">{{cite web|last1=Beck|first1=Kellen|title=Echo Fox signs 7 players to build largest fighting game roster in esports|url=http://mashable.com/2017/01/04/echo-fox-fgc-roster/#A_ErQO4O25qk|website=[[Mashable]]|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref> \n\nEcho Fox would continue growing their team with the signing of Korean and French Tekken pros Saint, JDCR and VorttexX-Shadow, bringing their roster up to thirteen players.<ref name=\"FOXTekken\">{{cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/fgc/echo-fox-sign-tekken-players-saint-jdcr-4689|title=Echo Fox acquires top talent in Tekken|last1=Nordmark|first1=Sam|website=[[Daily Dot|Dot eSports]]|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== ''Call of Duty'' ==\nOn May 13, 2016 Echo Fox added a ''Call of Duty'' team with a roster of Jeremy \"Neslo\" Olsen, Jordan \"Proof\" Cannon, Jonathan \"SinfuL\" Baez, and Josh \"Cyborg\" Kimpson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-call-of-duty-team/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521121802/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-call-of-duty-team/# |archive-date=May 21, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In November, all players except Neslo were dropped and replaced by Anthony \"Methodz\" Zinni, Teegan \"TcM\" McCarthy, and Tanner \"Mosh\" Clark.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/call-of-duty/echo-fox-announces-new-call-of-duty-roster-10087 |title=Echo Fox Announces New Call of Duty Roster |publisher=Dot Esports |date= |accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Echo Fox}}\n{{League of Legends Championship Series North America}}\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Esports teams based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Former North American League of Legends Championship Series teams]]\n[[Category:Fighting game player sponsors]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. player sponsors]]\n[[Category:Echo Fox| ]]\n[[Category:Venture capital-funded esports teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox sports team\n| name         = Echo Fox\n| short_name   =\n| logo         = Echo Fox logo.png\n| logo_size    =\n| alt          =\n| caption      =\n| city         =\n| location     =\n| parent_group =\n| founded      = {{start date|2015|12|18}}\n| folded       = November 2019\n| league       =\n| history      =\n| owner        = Khalid Jones (co-owner)\n| president    = Jared Jeffries\n| gm           = Justin Lee\n| partners     =\n| sport_label  = Divisions\n| sport        = ''[[Apex Legends]]''<br>''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]''<br>''[[Dragon Ball FighterZ]]''<br>''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]''<br>''[[Injustice 2]]''<br>''[[Madden NFL 19]]''<br>''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''<br>''[[Super Smash Bros.]]''<br>''[[Street Fighter V]]''\n| website      = {{Official URL}}\n| footnotes    =\n| fanclub      =\n}}\n\n'''Echo Fox''' was an American [[esports]] organization. It was founded on December 18, 2015 by retired basketball player [[Rick Fox]], who created Echo Fox after he purchased the [[North American League of Legends Championship Series|NA LCS]] spot of [[Gravity Gaming]].<ref name=\"BloombergFOX\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-18/former-nba-player-rick-fox-buys-esports-team-gravity|title=Former NBA Player Rick Fox Buys eSports Team Gravity|first=Scott |last=Soshnick|website=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2015}}</ref> The organization had expanded into various games with teams competing in titles such as ''[[Call of Duty]]'', ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive|CS:GO]]'', ''[[Dragon Ball FighterZ]]'', ''[[Injustice 2]],'' ''[[Madden NFL 19]]'', ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'', ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'', and ''[[Street Fighter V]]''. Echo Fox had several fighting game players with championship titles and are a well known organization in the professional scene.\n\n== Controversies ==\n[[File:Rick Fox 2009.jpg|thumb|Rick Fox, co-founder of Echo Fox.]]\n\nOn December 18, 2015 [[Rick Fox]] and his business partners, Amit Razaida and Khalid Jones, entered the professional [[esports]] scene with their acquisition of the [[North American League of Legends Championship Series|NA LCS]] spot of [[Gravity Gaming]], creating a new team named Echo Fox.<ref name=\"BloombergFOX\" /> According to Razaida, he and Jones \"both offered up $1 million each to get the new team off the ground\" while Fox \"never put in any of his own money into Echo Fox.\" Fox and Raizada subsequently had a falling out, in which Raizada claims Fox attempted to extort him of $5 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://upcomer.com/lol/story/1427355/raizada-comes-forward-to-dispute-allegations-by-fox|title=Exclusive: Raizada comes forward to dispute allegations by Fox|website=upcomer.com|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Fox threatened to leave the esports team after accusing Razaida of making racist comments against him and Echo Fox CEO Jace Hall, as well as threatening Fox's family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/esports/rick-fox-leaving-echo-fox-amid-racist-abuse-from-organization-shareholder-576426|title=Rick Fox set to leave Echo Fox amid racist abuse from organization shareholder [UPDATED]|website=Dexerto.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/4/25/18516539/rick-fox-leaving-echo-fox-racism-esports|title=Rick Fox reportedly quitting his esports company, alleging racist abuse|last=Lee|first=Julia|date=2019-04-25|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> In response, Riot Games, which operates the LCS, launched an investigation. It ordered Echo Fox to remove Razaida, or it would have to sell its spot in the LCS within 60 days, saying \"hate speech, threats, and bigotry have no place in the LCS.\" With Echo Fox unable to remove Razaida, Riot Games came up with an agreement to end Echo Fox's participation in the LCS. Kroenke Sports and Entertainment agreed to a deal for the LCS slot soon after for $30.25 million, however, the deal fell through due to legal issues with their partner, Sentinels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27358667/kroenke-sports-entertainment-deal-acquire-echo-fox-falls-through|title=Kroenke Sports & Entertainment deal to acquire Echo Fox falls through|date=2019-08-10|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> After the deadline given to Echo Fox to sell their slot ended, Riot Games announced its plans to sell off the newly vacated LCS franchise spot to a new team, with most of the proceeds going to Echo Fox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/14/20805868/league-of-legends-echo-fox-sale-lcs-riot-games|title=Riot Games steps in to find buyer for Echo Fox\u2019s League of Legends franchise|last=Goslin|first=Austen|date=2019-08-14|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nRiot games selected Evil Geniuses as the organization that would acquire Echo Fox's League Championship Series slot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27708703/evil-geniuses-confirm-acquisition-echo-fox-lcs-spot|title=Evil Geniuses confirm acquisition of Echo Fox's LCS spot|date=2019-09-26|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, A lawsuit ousting general partner [[Rick Fox]] was sent to Fox by several of his business partners, stating Fox had repeatedly worked against the best interests of the company. The letter sent had several signatures including: Vision Esports head Stratton Sclavos, investor Daniel Deshe, Raizada Group manager Ravi Srivastava and Khalid Jones, who was Fox's partner in the general partnership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27714092/rick-fox-ousted-echo-fox|title=Sources: Rick Fox to be ousted from Echo Fox|date=2019-09-27|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> \u00a0Fox filed a lawsuit against his business partners Amit Raizada and Stratton Sclavos alleging the two partners committed fraud, conspiracy and breach of contract against him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27759801/rick-fox-sues-business-partners-alleging-fraud-conspiracy-breach-contract|title=Rick Fox sues business partners alleging fraud, conspiracy and breach of contract|date=2019-10-03|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, with numerous rumors spreading about Echo Fox splitting apart over the lawsuits, an Echo Fox investor officially confirmed the organization was disbanded.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dotesports.com/business/news/echo-fox-reportedly-dissolves-parts-ways-with-players-and-staff |title=Echo Fox reportedly dissolves, parts ways with players and staff |date=2019-11-09 |website=Dot Esports |language=en-US |access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://win.gg/news/2920/echo-fox-investors-confirm-echo-fox-is-100-percent-dissolved |title=Echo Fox investors confirm Echo Fox is 100 percent dissolved - LOL - News - WIN.gg |last=Richman |first=Olivia |website=WIN Esports |access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n== ''League of Legends'' ==\nOn January 23, 2016, due to some concerns over player work-eligibility, Echo Fox was unable to submit a roster and was required to forfeit their match against [[NRG Esports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/competitive-ruling-echo-fox|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com|access-date=January 23, 2016}}</ref> Echo Fox finished last in the [[2016 Summer NA LCS]], forcing a relegation match. They defeated [[NRG Esports]] 3-0 in relegations and qualified for the 2017 NA LCS Spring Split.\n\nIn 2018, the North American [[League of Legends Championship Series#Franchising|League of Legends Championship Series]] moved to a franchised league and Echo Fox invested in a spot as a permanent partner. Echo Fox later received an equity investment from the [[New York Yankees]] and a new roster, which finished 2nd in the 2018 NA LCS Spring Split with 12 wins and 7 losses after losing a tiebreaker to [[100 Thieves]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NA LCS 2018 Spring Split {{!}} Teams and Standings|url=https://www.lolesports.com/en_US/na-lcs/na_2018_spring/standings/regular_season|website=www.lolesports.com|publisher=LoL Esports|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 16, 2019, the rosters of both Echo Fox and Echo Fox Academy were released, and the organization departed the professional ''League of Legends'' scene.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Jacob |title=Ousted from LCS, Echo Fox release players |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27402851/ousted-lcs-echo-fox-release-players |accessdate=September 26, 2019 |work=Field Level Media via ESPN |date=August 17, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== ''Counter-Strike: Global Offensive'' ==\nWhile no official reason has been given for Echo Fox allowing its players to leave, it is rumored that this was due to poor performances at both [[ELEAGUE Season 2]] and IBUYPOWER Masters 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hltv.org/news/19251/echo-fox-allows-players-to-exit|title=Echo Fox allows players to exit|work=HLTV.org|access-date=October 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref> At ELEAGUE, Echo Fox lost versus [[Virtus.pro]] (where they won only a single round on Nuke),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://esportlivescore.com/e_214950-virtuspro-vs-echo-fox-eleague.html|title=Virtus.pro vs Echo Fox - CSGO - match result - 05-11-2016|website=eSportLiveScore.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref> and versus [[G2 Esports]] (where Echo Fox lost 16\u20133 and 16\u20132 on Nuke and Dust 2 respectively).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gosugamers.net/counterstrike/tournaments/12417-eleague-season-2/matches/144301-echo-fox-vs-g2-esports|title=Echo Fox. vs G2 Esports - CS:GO - ELEAGUE Season 2 {{!}} GosuGamers|website=www.gosugamers.net|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref> At iBUYPOWER Masters 2016 Echo Fox finished a disappointing 5th\u20136th place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.12up.com/posts/4109078-echo-fox-struggles-at-ibp-masters-2016|title=Echo Fox Struggles at iBP Masters 2016|date=2016-11-14|website=12up.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\n== Fighting games ==\nEcho Fox entered the [[fighting game community]] on April 29, 2016 by signing ''[[Street Fighter V]]'' player Julio Fuentes.<ref name=\"FOXJulio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-fighting-games-sign-sfv-julio-fuentes/|title=Echo Fox gets into fighting games, sign SFV player Julio Fuentes|last1=Mueller|first1=Saira|last2=Jurek|first2=Steven|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|accessdate=April 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503075222/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-fighting-games-sign-sfv-julio-fuentes/|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> A month later, they would sign ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' pro [[Mew2King|Jason \"Mew2King\" Zimmerman]].<ref name=\"FOXM2K\">{{cite web|url=https://pvplive.net/c/echo-fox-signs-mew2king|title=Echo Fox Signs Mew2King|last1=Steiner|first1=Dustin|website=[[PVP Live]]|accessdate=May 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202050823/https://pvplive.net/c/echo-fox-signs-mew2king|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Echo Fox would make one of the biggest signings in [[esports]] history by signing seven FGC players all at once, three of which previously represented [[Evil Geniuses]]. The players were ''Street Fighter'' players [[Justin Wong]], Yusuke Momochi, Hajime \"Tokido\" Taniguchi, and Yuko \"ChocoBlanka\" Momochi, ''Mortal Kombat'' players [[SonicFox|Dominique \"SonicFox\" McLean]] and Brad \"Scar\" Vaughn, and ''Super Smash Bros.'' player [[MKLeo|Leonardo \"MKLeo\" Lopez Perez]]. At the same time, Echo Fox signed former Evil Geniuses manager Antonio \"CoolGrayAJ\" Javier as the team's new manager.<ref name=\"FOXFGC\">{{cite web|last1=Beck|first1=Kellen|title=Echo Fox signs 7 players to build largest fighting game roster in esports|url=http://mashable.com/2017/01/04/echo-fox-fgc-roster/#A_ErQO4O25qk|website=[[Mashable]]|accessdate=January 5, 2017}}</ref> \n\nEcho Fox would continue growing their team with the signing of Korean and French Tekken pros Saint, JDCR and VorttexX-Shadow, bringing their roster up to thirteen players.<ref name=\"FOXTekken\">{{cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/fgc/echo-fox-sign-tekken-players-saint-jdcr-4689|title=Echo Fox acquires top talent in Tekken|last1=Nordmark|first1=Sam|website=[[Daily Dot|Dot eSports]]|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== ''Call of Duty'' ==\nOn May 13, 2016 Echo Fox added a ''Call of Duty'' team with a roster of Jeremy \"Neslo\" Olsen, Jordan \"Proof\" Cannon, Jonathan \"SinfuL\" Baez, and Josh \"Cyborg\" Kimpson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-call-of-duty-team/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521121802/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/echo-fox-call-of-duty-team/# |archive-date=May 21, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In November, all players except Neslo were dropped and replaced by Anthony \"Methodz\" Zinni, Teegan \"TcM\" McCarthy, and Tanner \"Mosh\" Clark.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/call-of-duty/echo-fox-announces-new-call-of-duty-roster-10087 |title=Echo Fox Announces New Call of Duty Roster |publisher=Dot Esports |date= |accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Echo Fox}}\n{{League of Legends Championship Series North America}}\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Esports teams based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Former North American League of Legends Championship Series teams]]\n[[Category:Fighting game player sponsors]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. player sponsors]]\n[[Category:Echo Fox| ]]\n[[Category:Venture capital-funded esports teams]]\n", "name_user": "TheBigRed241", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citations 10 and 11 are dead links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Echo_Fox"}
{"title_page": "Pete Souza", "text_new": "{{short description|American photographer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Pete Souza\n|image         = Pete Souza and Politics at Prose-cropped.jpg\n|caption       = Souza in 2018\n| office        = [[Chief Official White House Photographer]]\n| term_start    = January 20, 2009\n| term_end      = January 20, 2017\n| president     = [[Barack Obama]]\n| predecessor   = [[Eric Draper]]\n| successor     = [[Shealah Craighead]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1954|12|31}}\n|birth_place   = {{nowrap|[[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.}}\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n|alma_mater= [[Boston University]]<br>[[Kansas State University]]\n|occupation    = [[White House]] [[Photographer]] (1983\u20131989)<br />Chief Official [[White House]] Photographer (2009\u20132017)\n|website       = {{url|petesouza.com|PeteSouza.com}}\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Patti Lease|2013}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/obama-photog-pete-souza-married-white-house-article-1.1491551|title=Obama photographer Pete Souza gets hitched in White House wedding...so who took the pictures?|first=Leslie|last=Larson|website=NY Daily News|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=September 30, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Peter Joseph Souza'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reaganlibrary.gov/sites/default/files/archives/audiovisual/portraitproject.pdf |title=Michael Evans Portrait Project Collection - 1981-1984 (120 mm negatives)}}</ref> (born December 31, 1954)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsyndicate.com/artist.php?artist=1141 |title=Art by Pete Souza |publisher=Museumsyndicate.com |date= |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Pete-Souza/e/B001K8KRQI |title=Pete Souza: Books, Biography, Blog, Audiobooks, Kindle |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> is an American [[photojournalism|photojournalist]], the former [[Chief Official White House Photographer]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. Presidents]] [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Barack Obama]] and the former director of the White House Photography Office.<ref name=wh>{{cite web |title=Open for Questions: Pete Souza on White House Photography |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2010/10/26/open-questions-pete-souza-white-house-photography |date=October 26, 2010  |publisher=[[White House]] website}}</ref> He was a photographer with ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'', stationed at the [[Washington, D.C.]], bureau from 1998 to 2007; during this period he also followed the rise of then-[[United States Senate|Senator]] Obama to the presidency.<ref name=pbs/><ref name=ohio/>\n\n==Early life==\nSouza was born in [[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]], [[Massachusetts]] and grew up in [[South Dartmouth, Massachusetts|South Dartmouth]], Massachusetts,<ref name=\"ps-bio\"/> the son of a nurse and a boat mechanic.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/09/us/politics/pete-souza-obama-photographer-book.html| title = Pete Souza Photographed the Obama Presidency. Now He Helps People Remember It|first=Katie|last=Rogers|website=New York Times|date=November 9, 2017 |accessdate = November 12, 2017 }}</ref> He is of [[Portuguese American|Portuguese ancestry]]; both sets of his grandparents emigrated from the [[Azores]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.pt/inicio/portugal/Interior.aspx?content_id=1716718&page=-1 |title=Cavaco sabia que os meus av\u00f3s eram dos A\u00e7ores |website=DN.pt |date=2010-11-21 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924043301/http://www.dn.pt/inicio/portugal/Interior.aspx?content_id=1716718&page=-1 |archivedate=2015-09-24 |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSouza graduated ''[[cum laude]]'' with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in public communication from [[Boston University]] and a [[master's degree]] in journalism and mass communication from [[Kansas State University]].<ref name=ohio/><ref name=\"ps-bio\">{{cite web | url = http://www.petesouza.com/content.html?page=3 | title = Bio | publisher = Pete Souza | accessdate = October 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nSouza started his career in the 1970s in [[Kansas]] at the ''Chanute Tribune'' and the ''[[Hutchinson News]]''.<ref name=abc>{{cite news |title=This Week\u2019s Podcast Interview: New White House Photographer Pete Souza|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2009/01/this-weeks-podc-5/ |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=January 15, 2009}}</ref> In the early 1980s, he was a photographer for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. He served as an official White House photographer for President [[Ronald Reagan]] from June 1983 until 1989. He was also the official photographer for the [[Death and state funeral of Ronald Reagan|funeral services of Ronald Reagan]] in 2004.<ref name=\"ps-bio\"/>\n\nAt the end of the Reagan administration, Souza continued to be based in [[Washington, D.C.]] Between 1998 and 2007, he was a photographer for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' Washington, D.C., bureau.<ref name=ohio/> Souza has also worked as a freelancer for ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]'' and ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazines. After the [[September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]], he was among the first journalists to cover the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]] and the fall of [[Kabul]].\n\n===With Barack Obama===\nIn 2004, [[Jeff Zeleny]], now a political correspondent  for [[CNN]], asked Souza to take photographs for a project documenting Barack Obama's first year as [[United States Senator|U.S. senator]].<ref name=wpost/>\n\nSouza covered Obama\u2019s arrival to the Senate in 2005 and met him for the first time on Obama's first day in the Senate. He documented Obama's time in the Senate, following him in many foreign trips, including those to [[Kenya]], [[South Africa]], and [[Russia]]. In the process he not only became close to Senator Obama, he ended up following his rise to the presidency.<ref name=pbs/> In July 2008, Souza published a bestseller [[photo-book]] ''The Rise of Barack Obama'', featuring photographs between 2005 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Front-Row View Of Obama's White House |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99353598 |date=January 15, 2009 |publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\nSouza was an assistant professor of photojournalism at [[Ohio University]]'s [[Ohio University#School of Visual Communication|School of Visual Communication]]<ref name=ohio>{{cite web |title=Faculty: Pete Souza, Assistant Professor |url=http://www.viscom.ohiou.edu/faculty_souza.phtml |date= |publisher=[[Ohio University#School of Visual Communication|Ohio University: School of Visual Communication]] }}</ref> After the November 2008 election, he was asked to become the official White House photographer for his second time for the new [[Presidential transition of Barack Obama|President-elect Obama]].<ref name=wpost>{{cite news |title=White House Photographer Pete Souza Has the Country's Top Photo Op: Pete Souza takes another turn as official White House photographer, this time to document President Barack Obama.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/02/26/AR2009022604280.html |publisher=Washington Post |date= March 1, 2009 |first=Manuel |last=Roig-Franzia}}</ref><ref name=wins>{{cite news|last=Winslow|first=Donald R.|title=Pete Souza Named Obama's White House Photographer|url=http://nppa.org/news_and_events/news/2009/01/souza.html|accessdate=May 14, 2012|newspaper=News Photographer|publisher=[[National Press Photographers Association]]|date=January 4, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513182957/http://nppa.org/news_and_events/news/2009/01/souza.html|archivedate=May 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  On January 14, 2009, the new [[Presidential portrait (United States)|presidential portrait]] was released; it is the first time that an official presidential portrait was taken with a digital camera.<ref>{{cite web |title=New official portrait released Wednesday |url=http://change.gov/newsroom/entry/new_official_portrait_released/ |date=January 14, 2009 |publisher= change.gov, [[Office of the President-Elect]]}}</ref> A week later Souza was present at [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|the inauguration]] and the following day he was the only photographer present for Obama's second swearing-in on Obama's first workday in the [[Oval Office]].<ref name=wpost/>\n\nIn May 2009, Souza began using [[Flickr]] as an official conduit for releasing White House photos.  The photos were initially posted with a [[Creative Commons Attribution]] license which required that the original photographers be credited.  Flickr later created a new license which identified them as \"United States Government Work\" which does not carry any copyright restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|last=Singel |first=Ryan |url=https://www.wired.com/epicenter/2009/05/flickr-creates-new-license-for-white-house-photos/ |title=Flickr Creates New License for White House Photos - wired.com - May 11, 2009 |publisher=wired.com |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>The photos, at https://www.flickr.com/photos/whitehouse/  are (as of January 4, 2009) posted with the following disclaimer, \"This official White House photograph is being made available only for publication by news organizations and/or for personal use printing by the subject(s) of the photograph. The photograph may not be manipulated in any way and may not be used in commercial or political materials, advertisements, emails, products, promotions that in any way suggests approval or endorsement of the President, the First Family, or the White House.\"</ref>\n\nIn 2010, ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]'' produced a program about Souza titled ''The President's Photographer,'' which featured Souza as the main subject while also covering the previous White House photographers.<ref name=pbs>{{cite web |title=The President's Photographer: 50 Years in the Oval Office  |url=https://www.pbs.org/programs/presidents-photographer/ |date= |publisher=[[PBS]] }}</ref>\n\nSouza's [[The Situation Room (photograph)|photograph taken at 4:06 pm on May 1, 2011]], in the [[Situation Room]] during the [[Death of Osama bin Laden|raid on Osama bin Laden]], featuring Obama, [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]], [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]], and others, quickly became an iconic image.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/lifestyle/style/situation-room.html |title=Breaking down the Situation Room |work=[[Washington Post]]  |date=May 5, 2011 |accessdate=February 19, 2015 }}</ref> It also became one of the most viewed images on Flickr.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yin |first=Sara |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2384896,00.asp |title='Situation Room' Shot of Obama, Clinton Nearly Flickr's 'Most-Viewed' Photo |publisher=Pcmag.com |date=May 4, 2011 |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs White House photographer, Souza traveled with the president to document each meeting, trip and encounter for historical record. Along with his staff, Souza produced up to 20,000 pictures a week.<ref name=pbs/>\n\nIn November 2011, Souza was included on ''[[The New Republic]]'s'' list of Washington's most-powerful, least-famous people.<ref>{{cite news | last = The Editors | title = Washington's Most Powerful, Least Famous People| url = http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/96131/washingtons-most-powerful-least-famous-people?passthru=ZTM3Y2VhYmZjNmIzMjllNzQ3MjMxOGEzMmJlZjg1NzI | work = The New Republic | date = November 3, 2011 | accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs well as using very high end cameras for his presidential photography, Souza occasionally took square shots on his [[iPhone]].<ref name=Verge>The Verge: [https://www.theverge.com/2015/12/23/10657396/the-white-house-iphone-photos-pete-souza-instagram A year at the White House as seen through an iPhone's lens - The Verge]</ref><ref name=CultofMac>[http://www.cultofmac.com/403435/how-the-official-white-house-photographer-uses-his-iphone/ How the official White House photographer uses his iPhone] - Cult of Mac</ref>\n\n===Post-Obama administration===\n[[File:Pete Souza Releases 'Intimate' Look At Former President Barack Obama In Office - Morning Joe - MSNBC.webm|thumb|right|thumbtime=00:30|200px|Interview with Pete Souza about his 2017 book. Video from MSNBC.]]\nIn 2017 Souza received a book deal from [[Little, Brown and Company]] to publish a book of photos from his tenure as [[Chief Official White House Photographer|White House photographer]] titled ''Obama: An Intimate Portrait: The Historic Presidency in Photographs''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/26/us/politics/pete-souza.html|title=Obama's Photographer Gains a New Following, and a Book Deal|first=Katie|last=Rogers|website=The New York Times|date=April 26, 2017|accessdate=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUpon [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|inauguration]] as president in 2017, Souza began sharing pictures of Obama on his [[Instagram]] account, often as critical commentary on the new administration. In April 2017, he had over one million [[Instagram]] followers, and reached two million followers in August 2018 as he continued to critique the Trump presidency through contrasting photographs of Obama.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/petesouza/ instagram.com], [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/26/us/politics/pete-souza.html nytimes.com]</ref> In 2018, he announced the release of a new book titled ''[[Shade: A Tale of Two Presidents]]'', juxtaposing the Obama and Trump administrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/23/books/pete-souza-shade-obama-trump.html|title=Pete Souza's 'Shade' Adapts His Instagram Trolling Into Book Form|first=Michael|last=Gold|website=The New York Times|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2019, Pete Souza and his family moved to [[Madison, Wisconsin]].<ref>https://madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/former-obama-photographer-who-now-makes-career-of-trolling-trump/article_6357bf4e-53fa-59a4-a304-7aedf105fb5c.html</ref>\n\n==Photographs==\n<center><gallery widths=\"210px\" heights=\"210px\">\nFile:Ronald Reagan presidential portrait.jpg|Second-term official portrait of [[Ronald Reagan]], June 1985\nFile:Official portrait of Barack Obama.jpg|First-term official portrait of [[Barack Obama]], January 2009\nFile:Obama and Biden await updates on bin Laden.jpg|The ''[[Situation Room (photograph)|Situation Room]]'' (2011) by Souza became one of the most-viewed on [[Flickr]].\n</gallery></center>\n\n==Photo books==\n* ''Unguarded Moments: Behind-the-scenes Photographs of President Reagan'', Tapestry Pr, 1997. {{ISBN|1-930819-37-4}}\n* ''Plebe summer at the U.S. Naval Academy: photographs''. P. Souza, 2003. {{ISBN|0-9729426-0-2}}\n* ''Images of Greatness: An Intimate Look at the Presidency of Ronald Reagan'', Triumph Books, 2004. {{ISBN|1-57243-701-4}}.\n* ''The Rise of Barack Obama'', Triumph Books, 2009. {{ISBN|1-60078-313-9}}.\n* ''The President's Photographer: Fifty Years Inside the Oval Office'', with John Bredar. National Geographic, 2010. {{ISBN|1-4262-0676-3}}.\n* ''Obama: An Intimate Portrait'', Little, Brown and Company, 2017. {{ISBN|0-3165-1258-3}}.\n* ''[[Shade: A Tale of Two Presidents]]'', Little, Brown and Company, 2018. {{ISBN|0-3164-2182-0}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pete Souza}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.petesouza.com/ }}\n* [http://www.musarium.com/stories/reagan/smallpages/02.html \"Unguarded Moments\"] of President Ronald Reagan\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/whitehouse/ Official White House Flickr Photostream]\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Chicago|Photography}}\n\n{{COWHP}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Souza, Pete}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from New Bedford, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Communications alumni]]\n[[Category:Kansas State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:White House photographers]]\n[[Category:Chicago Tribune people]]\n[[Category:American photojournalists]]\n[[Category:Ohio University faculty]]\n[[Category:Chicago Sun-Times people]]\n[[Category:Reagan administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Writers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Dartmouth, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American photographer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Pete Souza\n|image         = Pete Souza and Politics at Prose-cropped.jpg\n|caption       = Souza in 2018\n| office        = [[Chief Official White House Photographer]]\n| term_start    = January 20, 2009\n| term_end      = January 20, 2017\n| president     = [[Barack Obama]]\n| predecessor   = [[Eric Draper]]\n| successor     = [[Shealah Craighead]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1954|12|31}}\n|birth_place   = {{nowrap|[[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.}}\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n|alma_mater= [[Boston University]]<br>[[Kansas State University]]\n|occupation    = [[White House]] [[Photographer]] (1983\u20131989)<br />Chief Official [[White House]] Photographer (2009\u20132017)\n|website       = {{url|petesouza.com|PeteSouza.com}}\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Patti Lease|2013}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/obama-photog-pete-souza-married-white-house-article-1.1491551|title=Obama photographer Pete Souza gets hitched in White House wedding...so who took the pictures?|first=Leslie|last=Larson|website=NY Daily News|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=September 30, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Peter Joseph Souza'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reaganlibrary.gov/sites/default/files/archives/audiovisual/portraitproject.pdf |title=Michael Evans Portrait Project Collection - 1981-1984 (120 mm negatives)}}</ref> (born December 31, 1954)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsyndicate.com/artist.php?artist=1141 |title=Art by Pete Souza |publisher=Museumsyndicate.com |date= |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Pete-Souza/e/B001K8KRQI |title=Pete Souza: Books, Biography, Blog, Audiobooks, Kindle |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> is an American [[photojournalism|photojournalist]], the former [[Chief Official White House Photographer]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. Presidents]] [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Barack Obama]] and the former director of the White House Photography Office.<ref name=wh>{{cite web |title=Open for Questions: Pete Souza on White House Photography |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2010/10/26/open-questions-pete-souza-white-house-photography |date=October 26, 2010  |publisher=[[White House]] website}}</ref> He was a photographer with ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'', stationed at the [[Washington, D.C.]], bureau from 1998 to 2007; during this period he also followed the rise of then-[[United States Senate|Senator]] Obama to the presidency.<ref name=pbs/><ref name=ohio/>\n\n==Early life==\nSouza was born in [[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]], [[Massachusetts]] and grew up in [[South Dartmouth, Massachusetts|South Dartmouth]], Massachusetts,<ref name=\"ps-bio\"/> the son of a nurse and a boat mechanic.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/09/us/politics/pete-souza-obama-photographer-book.html| title = Pete Souza Photographed the Obama Presidency. Now He Helps People Remember It|first=Katie|last=Rogers|website=New York Times|date=November 9, 2017 |accessdate = November 12, 2017 }}</ref> He is of [[Portuguese American|Portuguese ancestry]]; both sets of his grandparents emigrated from the [[Azores]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.pt/inicio/portugal/Interior.aspx?content_id=1716718&page=-1 |title=Cavaco sabia que os meus av\u00f3s eram dos A\u00e7ores |website=DN.pt |date=2010-11-21 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924043301/http://www.dn.pt/inicio/portugal/Interior.aspx?content_id=1716718&page=-1 |archivedate=2015-09-24 |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSouza graduated ''[[cum laude]]'' with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in public communication from [[Boston University]] and a [[master's degree]] in journalism and mass communication from [[Kansas State University]].<ref name=ohio/><ref name=\"ps-bio\">{{cite web | url = http://www.petesouza.com/content.html?page=3 | title = Bio | publisher = Pete Souza | accessdate = October 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nSouza started his career in the 1970s in [[Kansas]] at the ''Chanute Tribune'' and the ''[[Hutchinson News]]''.<ref name=abc>{{cite news |title=This Week\u2019s Podcast Interview: New White House Photographer Pete Souza|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2009/01/this-weeks-podc-5/ |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=January 15, 2009}}</ref> In the early 1980s, he was a photographer for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. He served as an official White House photographer for President [[Ronald Reagan]] from June 1983 until 1989. He was also the official photographer for the [[Death and state funeral of Ronald Reagan|funeral services of Ronald Reagan]] in 2004.<ref name=\"ps-bio\"/>\n\nAt the end of the Reagan administration, Souza continued to be based in [[Washington, D.C.]] Between 1998 and 2007, he was a photographer for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' Washington, D.C., bureau.<ref name=ohio/> Souza has also worked as a freelancer for ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]'' and ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazines. After the [[September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]], he was among the first journalists to cover the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]] and the fall of [[Kabul]].\n\n===With Barack Obama===\nIn 2004, [[Jeff Zeleny]], now a political correspondent  for [[CNN]], asked Souza to take photographs for a project documenting Barack Obama's first year as [[United States Senator|U.S. senator]].<ref name=wpost/>\n\nSouza covered Obama\u2019s arrival to the Senate in 2005 and met him for the first time on Obama's first day in the Senate. He documented Obama's time in the Senate, following him in many foreign trips, including those to [[Kenya]], [[South Africa]], and [[Russia]]. In the process he not only became close to Senator Obama, he ended up following his rise to the presidency.<ref name=pbs/> In July 2008, Souza published a bestseller [[photo-book]] ''The Rise of Barack Obama'', featuring photographs between 2005 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Front-Row View Of Obama's White House |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99353598 |date=January 15, 2009 |publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Souza began using [[Flickr]] as an official conduit for releasing White House photos.  The photos were initially posted with a [[Creative Commons Attribution]] license which required that the original photographers be credited.  Flickr later created a new license which identified them as \"United States Government Work\" which does not carry any copyright restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|last=Singel |first=Ryan |url=https://www.wired.com/epicenter/2009/05/flickr-creates-new-license-for-white-house-photos/ |title=Flickr Creates New License for White House Photos - wired.com - May 11, 2009 |publisher=wired.com |date= |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>The photos, at https://www.flickr.com/photos/whitehouse/  are (as of January 4, 2009) posted with the following disclaimer, \"This official White House photograph is being made available only for publication by news organizations and/or for personal use printing by the subject(s) of the photograph. The photograph may not be manipulated in any way and may not be used in commercial or political materials, advertisements, emails, products, promotions that in any way suggests approval or endorsement of the President, the First Family, or the White House.\"</ref>\n\nSouza was an assistant professor of photojournalism at [[Ohio University]]'s [[Ohio University#School of Visual Communication|School of Visual Communication]]<ref name=ohio>{{cite web |title=Faculty: Pete Souza, Assistant Professor |url=http://www.viscom.ohiou.edu/faculty_souza.phtml |date= |publisher=[[Ohio University#School of Visual Communication|Ohio University: School of Visual Communication]] }}</ref> After the November 2008 election, he was asked to become the official White House photographer for his second time for the new [[Presidential transition of Barack Obama|President-elect Obama]].<ref name=wpost>{{cite news |title=White House Photographer Pete Souza Has the Country's Top Photo Op: Pete Souza takes another turn as official White House photographer, this time to document President Barack Obama.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/02/26/AR2009022604280.html |publisher=Washington Post |date= March 1, 2009 |first=Manuel |last=Roig-Franzia}}</ref><ref name=wins>{{cite news|last=Winslow|first=Donald R.|title=Pete Souza Named Obama's White House Photographer|url=http://nppa.org/news_and_events/news/2009/01/souza.html|accessdate=May 14, 2012|newspaper=News Photographer|publisher=[[National Press Photographers Association]]|date=January 4, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513182957/http://nppa.org/news_and_events/news/2009/01/souza.html|archivedate=May 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  On January 14, 2009, the new [[Presidential portrait (United States)|presidential portrait]] was released; it is the first time that an official presidential portrait was taken with a digital camera.<ref>{{cite web |title=New official portrait released Wednesday |url=http://change.gov/newsroom/entry/new_official_portrait_released/ |date=January 14, 2009 |publisher= change.gov, [[Office of the President-Elect]]}}</ref> A week later Souza was present at [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|the inauguration]] and the following day he was the only photographer present for Obama's second swearing-in on Obama's first workday in the [[Oval Office]].<ref name=wpost/>\n\nIn 2010, ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]'' produced a program about Souza titled ''The President's Photographer,'' which featured Souza as the main subject while also covering the previous White House photographers.<ref name=pbs>{{cite web |title=The President's Photographer: 50 Years in the Oval Office  |url=https://www.pbs.org/programs/presidents-photographer/ |date= |publisher=[[PBS]] }}</ref>\n\nSouza's [[The Situation Room (photograph)|photograph taken at 4:06 pm on May 1, 2011]], in the [[Situation Room]] during the [[Death of Osama bin Laden|raid on Osama bin Laden]], featuring Obama, [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]], [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]], and others, quickly became an iconic image.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/lifestyle/style/situation-room.html |title=Breaking down the Situation Room |work=[[Washington Post]]  |date=May 5, 2011 |accessdate=February 19, 2015 }}</ref> It also became one of the most viewed images on Flickr.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yin |first=Sara |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2384896,00.asp |title='Situation Room' Shot of Obama, Clinton Nearly Flickr's 'Most-Viewed' Photo |publisher=Pcmag.com |date=May 4, 2011 |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs White House photographer, Souza traveled with the president to document each meeting, trip and encounter for historical record. Along with his staff, Souza produced up to 20,000 pictures a week.<ref name=pbs/>\n\nIn November 2011, Souza was included on ''[[The New Republic]]'s'' list of Washington's most-powerful, least-famous people.<ref>{{cite news | last = The Editors | title = Washington's Most Powerful, Least Famous People| url = http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/96131/washingtons-most-powerful-least-famous-people?passthru=ZTM3Y2VhYmZjNmIzMjllNzQ3MjMxOGEzMmJlZjg1NzI | work = The New Republic | date = November 3, 2011 | accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs well as using very high end cameras for his presidential photography, Souza occasionally took square shots on his [[iPhone]].<ref name=Verge>The Verge: [https://www.theverge.com/2015/12/23/10657396/the-white-house-iphone-photos-pete-souza-instagram A year at the White House as seen through an iPhone's lens - The Verge]</ref><ref name=CultofMac>[http://www.cultofmac.com/403435/how-the-official-white-house-photographer-uses-his-iphone/ How the official White House photographer uses his iPhone] - Cult of Mac</ref>\n\n===Post-Obama administration===\n[[File:Pete Souza Releases 'Intimate' Look At Former President Barack Obama In Office - Morning Joe - MSNBC.webm|thumb|right|thumbtime=00:30|200px|Interview with Pete Souza about his 2017 book. Video from MSNBC.]]\nIn 2017 Souza received a book deal from [[Little, Brown and Company]] to publish a book of photos from his tenure as [[Chief Official White House Photographer|White House photographer]] titled ''Obama: An Intimate Portrait: The Historic Presidency in Photographs''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/26/us/politics/pete-souza.html|title=Obama's Photographer Gains a New Following, and a Book Deal|first=Katie|last=Rogers|website=The New York Times|date=April 26, 2017|accessdate=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUpon [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|inauguration]] as president in 2017, Souza began sharing pictures of Obama on his [[Instagram]] account, often as critical commentary on the new administration. In April 2017, he had over one million [[Instagram]] followers, and reached two million followers in August 2018 as he continued to critique the Trump presidency through contrasting photographs of Obama.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/petesouza/ instagram.com], [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/26/us/politics/pete-souza.html nytimes.com]</ref> In 2018, he announced the release of a new book titled ''[[Shade: A Tale of Two Presidents]]'', juxtaposing the Obama and Trump administrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/23/books/pete-souza-shade-obama-trump.html|title=Pete Souza's 'Shade' Adapts His Instagram Trolling Into Book Form|first=Michael|last=Gold|website=The New York Times|date=May 23, 2018|accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2019, Pete Souza and his family moved to [[Madison, Wisconsin]].<ref>https://madison.com/wsj/news/local/govt-and-politics/former-obama-photographer-who-now-makes-career-of-trolling-trump/article_6357bf4e-53fa-59a4-a304-7aedf105fb5c.html</ref>\n\n==Photographs==\n<center><gallery widths=\"210px\" heights=\"210px\">\nFile:Ronald Reagan presidential portrait.jpg|Second-term official portrait of [[Ronald Reagan]], June 1985\nFile:Official portrait of Barack Obama.jpg|First-term official portrait of [[Barack Obama]], January 2009\nFile:Obama and Biden await updates on bin Laden.jpg|The ''[[Situation Room (photograph)|Situation Room]]'' (2011) by Souza became one of the most-viewed on [[Flickr]].\n</gallery></center>\n\n==Photo books==\n* ''Unguarded Moments: Behind-the-scenes Photographs of President Reagan'', Tapestry Pr, 1997. {{ISBN|1-930819-37-4}}\n* ''Plebe summer at the U.S. Naval Academy: photographs''. P. Souza, 2003. {{ISBN|0-9729426-0-2}}\n* ''Images of Greatness: An Intimate Look at the Presidency of Ronald Reagan'', Triumph Books, 2004. {{ISBN|1-57243-701-4}}.\n* ''The Rise of Barack Obama'', Triumph Books, 2009. {{ISBN|1-60078-313-9}}.\n* ''The President's Photographer: Fifty Years Inside the Oval Office'', with John Bredar. National Geographic, 2010. {{ISBN|1-4262-0676-3}}.\n* ''Obama: An Intimate Portrait'', Little, Brown and Company, 2017. {{ISBN|0-3165-1258-3}}.\n* ''[[Shade: A Tale of Two Presidents]]'', Little, Brown and Company, 2018. {{ISBN|0-3164-2182-0}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pete Souza}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.petesouza.com/ }}\n* [http://www.musarium.com/stories/reagan/smallpages/02.html \"Unguarded Moments\"] of President Ronald Reagan\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/whitehouse/ Official White House Flickr Photostream]\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Chicago|Photography}}\n\n{{COWHP}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Souza, Pete}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from New Bedford, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Communications alumni]]\n[[Category:Kansas State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:White House photographers]]\n[[Category:Chicago Tribune people]]\n[[Category:American photojournalists]]\n[[Category:Ohio University faculty]]\n[[Category:Chicago Sun-Times people]]\n[[Category:Reagan administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Obama administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Writers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Dartmouth, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Spamalicious", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWith Barack Obama", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Souza"}
